"{\"uid\": \"salon.com-2024-08-03-olympics-black-hair\", \"text\": \"Simone Bilesis an Olympic powerhouse. Hercomebackat the 2024 ParisOlympicshas kept eyes glued to screens as she racks up gold medal after gold medal.  But Biles\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 dominance hasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t stopped critics from telling her to \\\"gel up\\\" and \\\"pin up\\\" her hair, or commenting, \\\"Her messy hair is a choice.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d The Olympian took to Instagram to\\u00c2respond, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cGonna hold your hand when I say this, next time you want to comment on a Black girl's hair, JUST DON'T.\\\"  This isn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t the first time Biles has received disparaging comments about her hair; it certainly won\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t be the last. This criticism is not a new experience for Black women but with the spotlight on them in high-profile sports, these athletes are drawing more attention \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 and inevitably, more people with opinions about their appearance.  From Biles and\\u00c2Gabby Douglas\\u00c2\\u00a0to\\u00c2\\u00a0Dominique Dawes and\\u00c2Sha\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099Carri Richardson, and many others, Black female Olympians are still pressured to explain themselves to hair critics despite the evolving education around Black hair.  Related  Before there were superstar Gen Z athletes like Biles, Douglas and Richardson, there was Dawes. In 1996, Dawes became the first Black person to win an individual Olympic medal in gymnastics. However, while in\\u00c2\\u00a0Atlanta, the 19-year-old was criticized for her hair being \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009caskew.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d She wore her pressed-out or relaxed hair in a slicked-back bun with a gold scrunchie. She also had wispy bangs to match.\\u00c2  Shesaidof the experience in 2012, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cAs gymnasts, we are not concerned about our hair. If you look back at videos of myself at the Olympics, you\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll see I wasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t so concerned with how I looked and if I was, I may have never made it to the Olympic games. My focus wasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t on appearance, it was on achievement.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  This isn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t the first time Biles has received disparaging comments about her hair; it certainly won\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t be the last.  Similarly, nearly 20 years after Dawes\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 gold win, 16-year-old Douglas entranced the country with her gymnastics at the 2012 London Olympics. She wore\\u00c2\\u00a0her hair straightened in a slicked-back ponytail, but even this style was targeted by\\u00c2\\u00a0both white and Black critics who called into question the edges of her hairline. In the Black community, if edges are not slicked back with gel or edge control, the appearance can be deemed as \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cunkept\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d and \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cembarrassing.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d\\u00c2  During the Rio Games in 2016, Douglassaid, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cDid I choose my hair texture? No. I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m grateful for having this hair on my head. When you read that hurtful stuff you\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re like \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0098OK, wow.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  In an article fromthe Daily Beast, a Black woman interviewed by the publication said, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI just hate the way [Douglas\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099] hair looks with all those pins and gel. I wish someone could have helped her make it look better since she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s being seen all over the world. She representing for Black women everywhere.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s taboo culturally to be seen in public with a kinky hairline and your ponytail is straight,\\\" celebrity hairstylist Larry Simms for Mary J. Blige and Gabrielle Union told The Daily Beast. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThe textures don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t match her own hair and the added-on hair, and that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s a problem. I think Black girls in particular view her as a representation of themselves for the world to see. She just needs some Smooth and Shine gel and she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099d be OK.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099  Daily Beast's reporter Allison Samuels explained, \\\"The texture of black and African-American hair varies, and extreme heat and sweat can cause the strands to revert to their natural state. Natural hair can be difficult to maintain and usually runs in sharp contrast with traditional society\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s idea of beauty.\\\"  Years later in 2020, Douglas\\u00c2shareda now-deleted social media post describing her complicated and much-talked-about relationship with her hair. It turns out that years of wearing the tight ponytail for gymnastics irreparably harmed her hair and even caused \\\"bald spots on the back of her hair.\\\" Eventually she cut off all of her hair because of the damage.  Unfortunately, the public ridicule also harmed Douglas emotionally as well. As a result she said she\\u00c2\\u00a0\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009ccried and cried and cried\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d over her damaged hair and the racist online trolling.  The perceived messiness is not the only issue Black Olympians have faced regarding their hair at the Games. One ruling tried to limit how Black swimmers performed by controlling what they wore. Many Black female swimmers\\u00c2\\u00a0worethe Soul Capbecause its extra-large design accommodates \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cthick, curly, or voluminous hair,\\\" features of Black hair texture and styles ranging from natural to braids.  However, three years ago, the International Swimming Federation (formerly FINA, now known as World Aquatics) banned those swim caps because they did not \\\"[follow] the natural form of the head,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d NPRreported. This decision was made by the governing body, because, to their \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cbest knowledge, the athletes competing at the international events never used, neither require to use, caps of such size and configuration,\\\"according to the AP.  Simply put, Black hair is not allowed to be Black hair.  Unfortunately, this decision revealed just how limited the scope of who was historically welcomed to swim in public.\\u00c2\\u00a0The ban was met with backlash from athletes like Black British swimmer Alice Dearing, whotold The Guardian, \\\"Back in the 1960s, I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve seen those images of a black woman in a swimming pool and a white man pouring acid into it while she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s there. And there were instances where Black people were just outright banned from pools. So it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s not really a surprise that we get to 2020 or the 21st century and we see these issues occurring and there\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s a lack of Black people in swimming, because it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s just been decades and decades of historical and cultural racism.\\\"  Fewer Black swimmers (and competitive swimmers at that) meant that World Aquatics \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 which is based in Switzerland where the Black population is in the minority andfaces racism\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 based their decision on the majority of swimmers with thinner hair that would lay flatter on the head, not on Black hair textures.\\u00c2\\u00a0Soul Capstated,\\u00c2\\u00a0\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cTraditional swimming caps often do not accommodate these hair types, hindering participation.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d\\u00c2  Fortunately, the decision to ban the caps wasreversedin 2022 after it went under a year of review and discussion with the cap's creators. Soul Cap said the approval \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cis a huge step in the right direction \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 bringing inclusive swimwear into competitive swimming, and helping to bring down some of the obstacles that are keeping swimmers away from the sport.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  In a few years, we have come a long way. In 2024, Simone Manuel, the first Black woman to win an individual gold medal in swimming, created her own foundation to provide equity for communities of color to increase positive swimming experiences. She also has publiclysharedher hair care routine in and out of the pool.  Another example of this defiance is with sprinter Sha'carri Richardson, who is no stranger to criticism, especially after having been disqualified previously from the Olympics for testing positive for marijuana. Following that, Richardson was ridiculed with countless racistcommentscalling her \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009chood-rat,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cghetto\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d and \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009clow-life\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 often aimed at how she decided to present herself with false eyelashes, bold wigs and long, decorated nails.\\u00c2  Despite the noise, the runner continues to wear her power through her colorful array of wigs, ranging from blue, blonde, and red to her signature orange. She hasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t only worn wigs either. Last year, in a viral clip before a race, Richardson tossed off her orange wig to reveal hidden silver ombre braids.    She's also been known to sport braids that are rainbow-colored, mermaid green and more. Never content with just one look, Richardson also stunned in a new Olay advertisement with her natural curls. In a Vogueinterview, the track star acknowledged how she is perceived but said, \\\"I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m not gonna change the confidence that I have in myself ever.\\\"  We need your help to stay independent  Incremental changes like reversing the Soul Cap ban thatappear to accept more Black hairstylesfrom athletes have been made.\\u00c2\\u00a0Our evolving culture has unlocked larger conversations about Black hair education. There have been documentaries like \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cHair Tales\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d and Oscar-winning short films like\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cHair Love.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009dThey have highlighted the sensitivities and cultural connections Black people have to hair.    Unfortunately, there is still evidence that Black female Olympians will always be held to incredibly high standards. Their hair must be respectable. It should be digestible so audiences feel comfortable watching them. The athlete\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s comfort does not matter.\\u00c2  Biles\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 response to this: \\\"Do not come for me about my hair.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  This inappropriate scrutiny is partly fueled by ignorance about the realities and cultural meanings attached to Black hair. Black hair is not easily defined; it is not a one-size-fits-all category. It is versatile. Not one Black person\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s hair is exactly the same as the next. But even with that knowledge, there is still a level of misogynoir that is perpetuated by both non-Black and Black people alike who feel that Black hair has to look one specific way.  Simply put, Black hair is not allowed to be Black hair.  Black hair can\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t coil. It can\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t curl. It can\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t frizz. It has to be slicked back with pounds of gel \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 not an edge out of place. Respectable and kept. Even if you are the most decorated gymnast of all time.  Read more  about this topic  \\u00c2  Copyright \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026 Salon.com, LLC. Reproduction of material from any Salon pages without written permission is strictly prohibited. SALON \\u00c2\\u00ae is registered in the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office as a trademark of Salon.com, LLC. Associated Press articles: Copyright \\u00c2\\u00a9 2016 The Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed.  DMCA Policy  By subscribing, you agree that Salon will automatically charge you at the then-current rate (currently $9.95/month or $95/year) each month/year until you cancel. Log in to your account anytime to cancel prior to renewal date and avoid future charges.  Your current signup type is\"}"